\par\plain {\f1\fs36\b0\i0\cf3 Mac vs. Windows Scrivener}
\par\pard\plain \tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The Mac version is much nicer and gets alot more updates from the folks who make Scrivener. Their version numbering is a little confusing. The Mac and Win versions are not directly compatible, but if you EXPORT from the Mac version to \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Scrivener 2 format\u8221\'94 then you can open the project in the Win version.  To re-open it in the Mac version after editing in Win version, I think you have to import it, but might be able to open it directly. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 There is also a Linux version that is similar to the Win version. Same thing applies. Can open the (Mac) \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Scrivener 2 format\u8221\'94 projects. It uses qt4, so there is a little bit of config that can be done from qtconfig. (See: https://www.wayoflinux.com/blog/scrivener-returns)}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
