\par\plain {\f1\fs36\b0\i0\cf3 Sample Documents}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Sample Output\u8221\'94 folder inside the Research folder contains examples of documents that have been created by compiling from this template. \u8220\'93Standard Manuscript\u8221\'94 shows the results when compiling to \u8220\'93Manuscript (Courier)\u8221\'94, and \u8220\'93Paperback Novel\u8221\'94 shows the results when compiling to \u8220\'93Paperback (5.06\u8221\'94 x 7.81\u8221\'94)\u8221\'94 format.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs36\b0\i0\cf3 Final Note}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Scrivener project templates are flexible and are not intended to restrict you to a particular workflow. You can change, delete or move the files and folders contained in the template to suit how you work.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Like all templates in Scrivener, this project was originally created from the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Blank\u8221\'94 template. We\u8217\'92ve simply added a few folders and set everything up in ways that should be useful to novel writers. Everything you can do with this project, you could equally do by creating a \u8220\'93Blank\u8221\'94 project and setting it up yourself.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 You can create your own templates by setting up a skeletal project with the files, folders and settings you would like to use for new projects and using File > Save As Template.}}